Note: ========================================
Note: ARM to HIR Translator
Note: ========================================
Note: Translates ARM Assembly AST to High-level Intermediate Representation
Note: Part of the Translation translation system
Note: Preserves instructions, operands, labels, and directives
Note: ========================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/arm/arm_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

Note: AST node type constants (must match arm_parser.runa)
Constant ARM_INSTRUCTION as Integer is 1
Constant ARM_DIRECTIVE as Integer is 2
Constant ARM_LABEL as Integer is 3
Constant ARM_REGISTER as Integer is 4
Constant ARM_IMMEDIATE as Integer is 5
Constant ARM_MEMORY as Integer is 6
Constant ARM_REGISTER_LIST as Integer is 7
Constant ARM_SHIFTED as Integer is 8
Constant ARM_IDENTIFIER as Integer is 9

@Reasoning:
Top-level entry that flattens the ARM parser's tree into a HIR document
shaped as a dictionary with "type"=arm_assembly plus three parallel lists
(instructions, directives, labels). Categorising at translation time means
downstream consumers (validator, codegen) can index directly without
re-walking the AST.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Guards on a 0 AST. Creates a Dict, stamps type=arm_assembly. Allocates three
empty Lists. Iterates the root's children, dispatches on node_type to
translate_instruction / translate_directive / translate_label, and pushes
non-null results into the matching list. Stores all three lists into the
HIR dict under "instructions", "directives", "labels". Returns the dict.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) over AST nodes plus O(d) over dictionary operations. Single pass over
the top-level statements; deep recursion handled by per-statement helpers.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "translate_arm_to_hir" takes arm_ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Main entry point - translate ARM AST to HIR dictionary

    If arm_ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let hir be proc create from Dict

    Note: Set HIR document type
    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "arm_assembly"
    proc set from Dict with hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Create lists for different statement types
    Let instructions be proc create from List
    Let directives be proc create from List
    Let labels be proc create from List

    Note: Process all children of root AST node
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with arm_ast, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get from List with children, i
        Let child_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child, 0

        If child_type is equal to ARM_INSTRUCTION:
            Let instr_hir be proc translate_instruction from child
            If instr_hir is not equal to 0:
                proc push from List with instructions, instr_hir
            End If
        End If

        If child_type is equal to ARM_DIRECTIVE:
            Let dir_hir be proc translate_directive from child
            If dir_hir is not equal to 0:
                proc push from List with directives, dir_hir
            End If
        End If

        If child_type is equal to ARM_LABEL:
            Let label_hir be proc translate_label from child
            If label_hir is not equal to 0:
                proc push from List with labels, label_hir
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Add collections to HIR
    Let instrs_key be proc create_string_literal with "instructions"
    proc set from Dict with hir, instrs_key, instructions

    Let dirs_key be proc create_string_literal with "directives"
    proc set from Dict with hir, dirs_key, directives

    Let labels_key be proc create_string_literal with "labels"
    proc set from Dict with hir, labels_key, labels

    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lowers an ARM_INSTRUCTION AST node into a {type, mnemonic, operands} HIR
dict. Operand translation is delegated to translate_operand so that
instruction lowering does not have to know about each operand kind.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a dict, sets type="instruction". Reads value_ptr/length from offsets
8/16 and (when non-empty) builds a Runa String for the mnemonic, stored
under "mnemonic". Walks the children list, calls translate_operand on each,
collects non-null results into an "operands" List stored on the dict.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(operand count) plus O(1) dict writes.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "translate_instruction" takes instr_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate instruction node to HIR dictionary

    Let instr_hir be proc create from Dict

    Note: Set type
    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "instruction"
    proc set from Dict with instr_hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Extract instruction mnemonic
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instr_node, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instr_node, 16
    If value_length is greater than 0:
        Let mnemonic_str be proc create_string_from_buffer from StringCore with value_ptr, value_length
        Let mnemonic_key be proc create_string_literal with "mnemonic"
        proc set from Dict with instr_hir, mnemonic_key, mnemonic_str
    End If

    Note: Process operands
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instr_node, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children

    Let operands be proc create from List
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get from List with children, i
        Let operand_hir be proc translate_operand from child
        If operand_hir is not equal to 0:
            proc push from List with operands, operand_hir
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let operands_key be proc create_string_literal with "operands"
    proc set from Dict with instr_hir, operands_key, operands

    Return instr_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lowers an ARM_DIRECTIVE node into a {type, name, arguments} dict. Mirrors
translate_instruction structurally because the AST shapes for directives
and instructions are parallel (lexeme + operand list); only the schema
keys differ ("name"/"arguments" vs "mnemonic"/"operands").
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a dict with type="directive". Reads the directive lexeme from
offsets 8/16 (including the leading '.') and stores under "name". Iterates
children, translates each via translate_operand, and pushes non-null
results into an "arguments" List on the dict.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(argument count).
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "translate_directive" takes dir_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate directive node to HIR dictionary

    Let dir_hir be proc create from Dict

    Note: Set type
    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "directive"
    proc set from Dict with dir_hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Extract directive name
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dir_node, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dir_node, 16
    If value_length is greater than 0:
        Let name_str be proc create_string_from_buffer from StringCore with value_ptr, value_length
        Let name_key be proc create_string_literal with "name"
        proc set from Dict with dir_hir, name_key, name_str
    End If

    Note: Process directive arguments
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with dir_node, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children

    Let arguments be proc create from List
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get from List with children, i
        Let arg_hir be proc translate_operand from child
        If arg_hir is not equal to 0:
            proc push from List with arguments, arg_hir
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let args_key be proc create_string_literal with "arguments"
    proc set from Dict with dir_hir, args_key, arguments

    Return dir_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
A label is just a named anchor; the HIR only needs the label's name and a
type tag. No operands are involved, so no child walk is required.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a dict with type="label". Reads name lexeme from offsets 8/16,
stores under "name" if non-empty.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_label" takes label_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate label node to HIR dictionary

    Let label_hir be proc create from Dict

    Note: Set type
    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "label"
    proc set from Dict with label_hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Extract label name
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with label_node, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with label_node, 16
    If value_length is greater than 0:
        Let name_str be proc create_string_from_buffer from StringCore with value_ptr, value_length
        Let name_key be proc create_string_literal with "name"
        proc set from Dict with label_hir, name_key, name_str
    End If

    Return label_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single dispatcher for the closed set of ARM operand kinds (register,
immediate, memory, register_list, shifted, identifier). Centralising the
switch keeps callers in instructions/directives identical and ensures every
operand kind round-trips to a well-known HIR schema.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-safe (returns 0 on a 0 node). Reads node_type at offset 0 and routes:
ARM_REGISTER -> translate_register, ARM_IMMEDIATE -> translate_immediate,
ARM_MEMORY -> translate_memory, ARM_REGISTER_LIST -> translate_register_list,
ARM_SHIFTED -> translate_shifted, ARM_IDENTIFIER -> translate_identifier.
Unknown node types return 0 so the caller can skip them.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_operand" takes operand_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate operand node to HIR dictionary

    If operand_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with operand_node, 0

    If node_type is equal to ARM_REGISTER:
        Return proc translate_register from operand_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to ARM_IMMEDIATE:
        Return proc translate_immediate from operand_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to ARM_MEMORY:
        Return proc translate_memory from operand_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to ARM_REGISTER_LIST:
        Return proc translate_register_list from operand_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to ARM_SHIFTED:
        Return proc translate_shifted from operand_node
    End If

    If node_type is equal to ARM_IDENTIFIER:
        Return proc translate_identifier from operand_node
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers lower to a minimal {type, name} dict. Register-bank validation
(legal register set, sp/lr/pc aliasing) is deferred to semantic analysis;
this layer just preserves the lexeme.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a dict with type="register". Reads value lexeme from offsets 8/16
and stores under "name" if non-empty.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_register" takes reg_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate register operand to HIR

    Let reg_hir be proc create from Dict

    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "register"
    proc set from Dict with reg_hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Extract register name
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with reg_node, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with reg_node, 16
    If value_length is greater than 0:
        Let name_str be proc create_string_from_buffer from StringCore with value_ptr, value_length
        Let name_key be proc create_string_literal with "name"
        proc set from Dict with reg_hir, name_key, name_str
    End If

    Return reg_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Immediates lower to {type, value} preserving the textual representation
(e.g. '0xFF', '#42'). Numeric conversion is deferred so the HIR can still
carry hex/dec/bin forms for diagnostics and round-trip printing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a dict with type="immediate". Reads value lexeme from offsets 8/16
and stores under "value" if non-empty.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_immediate" takes imm_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate immediate value to HIR

    Let imm_hir be proc create from Dict

    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "immediate"
    proc set from Dict with imm_hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Extract immediate value
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with imm_node, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with imm_node, 16
    If value_length is greater than 0:
        Let value_str be proc create_string_from_buffer from StringCore with value_ptr, value_length
        Let value_key be proc create_string_literal with "value"
        proc set from Dict with imm_hir, value_key, value_str
    End If

    Return imm_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Memory references decompose into {type, base, offset?, writeback?}. The
arm_parser produces children in a fixed positional order (base, optional
offset, optional writeback sentinel), and we recover the schema by indexing
those positions rather than tagging children in the AST.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates dict type="memory". Walks children list by index: child 0 is the
base register, extracted as a raw string via get_operand_value_string and
stored under "base". Child 1, if present, is the offset, lowered recursively
via translate_operand and stored under "offset". Child 2's mere presence
signals writeback; we store writeback="true" without inspecting the child
(it is the sentinel ARM_IDENTIFIER from arm_parser.parse_memory).
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_memory" takes mem_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate memory reference to HIR

    Let mem_hir be proc create from Dict

    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "memory"
    proc set from Dict with mem_hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Process memory reference components (base, offset, writeback)
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mem_node, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children

    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Note: First child is base register
        Let base_child be proc get from List with children, 0
        Let base_str be proc get_operand_value_string from base_child
        Let base_key be proc create_string_literal with "base"
        proc set from Dict with mem_hir, base_key, base_str
    End If

    If child_count is greater than 1:
        Note: Second child is offset
        Let offset_child be proc get from List with children, 1
        Let offset_hir be proc translate_operand from offset_child
        Let offset_key be proc create_string_literal with "offset"
        proc set from Dict with mem_hir, offset_key, offset_hir
    End If

    If child_count is greater than 2:
        Note: Third child indicates writeback
        Let writeback_key be proc create_string_literal with "writeback"
        Let writeback_value be proc create_string_literal with "true"
        proc set from Dict with mem_hir, writeback_key, writeback_value
    End If

    Return mem_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Register lists (LDM/STM/PUSH/POP) lower to {type, registers} where
registers is a List of register HIR dicts. We re-use translate_operand for
each child so range expansion or future shifted-list extensions only need
to be implemented once.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates dict type="register_list". Iterates children, calls translate_operand
on each, collects non-null results into a "registers" List on the dict.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(register count). Typically <= 16.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "translate_register_list" takes reglist_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate register list to HIR

    Let reglist_hir be proc create from Dict

    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "register_list"
    proc set from Dict with reglist_hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Process registers in list
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with reglist_node, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children

    Let registers be proc create from List
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get from List with children, i
        Let reg_hir be proc translate_operand from child
        If reg_hir is not equal to 0:
            proc push from List with registers, reg_hir
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let registers_key be proc create_string_literal with "registers"
    proc set from Dict with reglist_hir, registers_key, registers

    Return reglist_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
A shifted operand 'Rm, LSL #imm' carries three pieces (base register, shift
op mnemonic, shift amount). Lowering to {type, register, shift_op,
shift_amount} keeps these decoupled so codegen can pattern-match each
piece independently.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates dict type="shifted". Reads child 0 as the base register and lowers
recursively via translate_operand, stored under "register". Reads child 1
as the shift operator and extracts its raw lexeme (LSL/LSR/ASR/ROR) via
get_operand_value_string, stored under "shift_op". Reads child 2 as the
shift amount and lowers recursively via translate_operand, stored under
"shift_amount". All three children are optional; missing ones leave the
key absent.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_shifted" takes shifted_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate shifted operand to HIR

    Let shifted_hir be proc create from Dict

    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "shifted"
    proc set from Dict with shifted_hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Process shift components (register, shift op, shift amount)
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with shifted_node, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children

    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Note: First child is base register
        Let base_child be proc get from List with children, 0
        Let base_hir be proc translate_operand from base_child
        Let base_key be proc create_string_literal with "register"
        proc set from Dict with shifted_hir, base_key, base_hir
    End If

    If child_count is greater than 1:
        Note: Second child is shift operator
        Let shift_op_child be proc get from List with children, 1
        Let shift_op_str be proc get_operand_value_string from shift_op_child
        Let shift_op_key be proc create_string_literal with "shift_op"
        proc set from Dict with shifted_hir, shift_op_key, shift_op_str
    End If

    If child_count is greater than 2:
        Note: Third child is shift amount
        Let shift_amt_child be proc get from List with children, 2
        Let shift_amt_hir be proc translate_operand from shift_amt_child
        Let shift_amt_key be proc create_string_literal with "shift_amount"
        proc set from Dict with shifted_hir, shift_amt_key, shift_amt_hir
    End If

    Return shifted_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
A bare identifier in operand position is a symbol or label reference. Lowers
to {type, name}. The HIR layer does not resolve the symbol; downstream
linking handles that.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates dict type="identifier". Reads value lexeme from offsets 8/16 and
stores under "name" if non-empty.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_identifier" takes ident_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate identifier (symbol) to HIR

    Let ident_hir be proc create from Dict

    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "identifier"
    proc set from Dict with ident_hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Extract identifier name
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ident_node, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ident_node, 16
    If value_length is greater than 0:
        Let name_str be proc create_string_from_buffer from StringCore with value_ptr, value_length
        Let name_key be proc create_string_literal with "name"
        proc set from Dict with ident_hir, name_key, name_str
    End If

    Return ident_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Small helper used where the lowerer wants the raw lexeme of an operand
(not a wrapped dict) - e.g. when storing the memory base or the shift
operator. Returns an empty string instead of 0 so callers can store the
result into a Dict without a null check.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads value_ptr/length from offsets 8/16. If length > 0, materialises a
Runa String from the byte range via create_string_from_buffer. Otherwise
returns a fresh empty string literal.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_operand_value_string" takes operand_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Extract value string from operand node

    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with operand_node, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with operand_node, 16
    If value_length is greater than 0:
        Return proc create_string_from_buffer from StringCore with value_ptr, value_length
    End If
    Return proc create_string_literal with ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
Thin alias for StringCore.create_string_from_literal so the file's
translation helpers can use a short local name and we have a single place
to add interning, caching, or memory-tracking later without touching every
call site.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
One-line wrapper delegating directly to StringCore.create_string_from_literal.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_string_literal" takes value as String returns Integer:
    Return proc create_string_from_literal from StringCore with value
End Process
